TY  - JOUR
AB  - Evidence suggests that people understand qualitatively how tastes change over time, but underestimate the magnitudes. This evidence is limited, however, to laboratory evidence or surveys of reported happiness. We test for such projection bias in field data. Using data on catalog orders of cold-weather items, we find evidence of projection bias over the weather-specifically, people's decisions are overinfluenced by the current weather. Our estimates suggest that if the order-date temperature declines by 300&#xb0;F, the return probability increases by 3.95 percent. We also estimate a structural model to measure the magnitude of the bias.
AU  - Conlin, Michael
AU  - O'Donoghue, Ted
